  "summary": "Rolly encounters a tall, tanned stranger with blue eyes and a beard who asks for directions to Froebel's, a white house on a hill. Rolly identifies the resident as Mrs. Gordon Clout. The stranger, who appears to have a colonial accent, departs toward the Wormsley Valley, leaving Rolly feeling a sense of familiarity regarding the man's face. Later that evening, Rolly visits the Stagg Saloon and asks the bartender, Beatrice Lippincott, about the stranger. Beatrice consults her guest ledger and identifies the man as Enock Yadon (later referred to as Enoch Yate) from Cape Town.\n\nThe following morning, David Hunter and Rosaline are having breakfast when David opens a letter addressed to him. The letter, written by Enoch Yate, claims to have news regarding Lieutenant Robert André that may shock \"Mrs. Claude\" (Rosaline). Yate, who is staying in Stagg, invites David to visit him that night to discuss the matter. David, unsettled by the letter's vague wording and the use of quotation marks around \"Mrs. Claude,\" perceives the message as a potential threat. To protect Rosaline, David instructs her to pack her bags and immediately move to an apartment in London, telling her to avoid all visitors. That night, David goes to the Stagg to find Yate. Beatrice Lippincott informs him that Enock Yate is staying in Room 5 on the second floor.",
